 repo and shall not be freed by the user.

Create a new Git index object as a memory representation

 to back it.

64.description:
Open the Index inside the git repository pointed
 by 'repo'.

65.name: git_index_clear
65.description:
Clear the contents (all the entries) of an index object.
 This clears the index object in memory; changes must be manually
 written to disk for them to take effect.

67.description:
Update the contents of an existing index object in memory
 by reading from the hard disk.

68.name: git_index_write
68.description:
Write an existing index object from memory back to disk
 using an atomic file lock.

69.description:
Find the first index of any entires which point to given
 path in the Git index.

70.description: Add or update an index entry from a file in disk.

71.description: Remove an entry from the index

72.name: git_index_insert
72.description:
Insert an entry into the index.
 A full copy (including the 'path' string) of the given
 'source_entry' will be inserted on the index; if the index
 already contains an entry for the same path, the entry
 will be updated.

73.description: Get a pointer to one of the entries in the index

105.description: Size (in bytes) of a hex formatted oid

106.description: Unique identity of any object (commit, tree, blob, tag).

107.description: Parse a hex formatted object id into a git_oid.

108.description: Copy an already raw oid into a git_oid structure.

109.name: git_oid_fmt
109.description: Format a git_oid into a hex string.

110.name: git_oid_pathfmt
110.description:
Format a git_oid into a loose-object path string.
 

 The resulting string is "aa/...", where "aa" is the first two
 hex digitis of the oid and "..." is the remaining 38 digits.

111.name: git_oid_allocfmt
111.description: Format a gid_oid into a newly allocated c-string.

112.name: git_oid_to_string
112.description:
Format a git_oid into a buffer as a hex format c-string.
 

 If the buffer is smaller than GIT_OID_HEXSZ+1, then the resulting
 oid c-string will be truncated to n-1 characters. If there are
 any input parameter errors (out == NULL, n == 0, oid == NULL),
 then a pointer to an empty string is returned, so that the return
 value can always be printed.

113.name: git_oid_cpy
113.description: Copy an oid from one structure to another.

Add a new OID to set of shortened OIDs and calculate

144.name: GIT_SORT_NONE
144.description: Sort the repository contents in no particular ordering; this sorting is arbitrary, implementation-specific and subject to change at any time. This is the default sorting for new walkers.

145.name: GIT_SORT_TOPOLOGICAL
145.description: Sort the repository contents in topological order (parents before children); this sorting mode can be combined with time sorting.

146.name: GIT_SORT_TIME
146.description: Sort the repository contents by commit time; this sorting mode can be combined with topological sorting.

147.name: GIT_SORT_REVERSE
147.description: Iterate through the repository contents in reverse order; this sorting mode can be combined with any of the above.
